description:
Farmhouse Kitchen's prices are somewhat expensive, although justifiably. From the creative plating to the intriguing food coloring (yes, I'm referring to the blue rice; yes, it tastes exactly the same as white rice), all their dishes come in beautiful presentations. There are also "specialty dish" carts that periodically swing by each table dim sum style. From these, I sampled the grasshopper (no, it wasn't because of a dare; no, it wasn't my first time eating insect) and we all shared the hoi tod, which is a fried mussels pancake.

// Neua Num Tok Rolls ($14) - 4 stars
Extremely flavorful slices of Wagyu flank steak. Unfortunately, they were also a little overcooked. Would have earned a perfect score if the meat were more tender.

// Mok Salmon Special ($19) - 3 stars
The fish was dry, bland, and on the smaller side.

// Kai Yang, Som Tum ($20) - 4 stars
The BBQ chicken had the perfect smokey aftertaste. I also liked how spicy the papaya salad was, but thought the black sticky rice was particularly hard. When initially ordering this dish, I actually tried substituting out the sticky rice for more salad, but our server wouldn't let me.

// Hat Yai Fried Chicken ($19) - 5 stars
I'm the biggest sucker for fried chicken, especially when it's drenched in curry sauce. Quite a filling meal, with all the roti bread and blue rice on the side.

// Thai Vacation ($9.50) - 4 stars
Very cutely plated inside a fresh coconut, the Thai Vacation is a mixture of black sticky rice, vanilla ice cream, coconut cream, peanuts, and black sesame.
